===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|penne||enclosure for animals}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|penn||enclosure, fold, pen}} (in compounds), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*pennō}}, {{m|gem-pro|*pannijō||pin, bolt, nail, tack}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bend-||pointed peg, nail, edge}}. Akin to {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|pennian||to close, lock, bolt}} (in compounds {{m|ang|onpennian||to open}}), {{etyl|nds|-}} {{m|nds|pennen||to secure a door with a bolt}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{m|ang|pinn||peg, bolt}}. More at [[pin]].

Sense “prison” originally figurative extension to enclosure for persons (1845), later influenced by {{term|penitentiary||prison|lang=en}}, being analyzed as an abbreviation (1884).<ref name="oetyld">{{R:Online Etymology Dictionary}}</ref>

